         <abstract>
            <p>In this paper the author uses principles of portfolio selection to define a perfectly random world and show how modern portfolio theory can provide a more sensitive framework for testing certain kinds of departures from the random walk hypothesis. When the model is examined in conjunction with empirical evidence that has accumulated over long periods of time, we are forced to conclude: (1) that the stock market has not been as random as many economists have supposed, (2) that Levy's evidence in support of nonrandomness for the period from 1960-1965 is not an unbiased refutation of the random walk hypothesis, and (3) that the principle of relative strength is not likely to be of practical long run value to investors after taxes and transaction costs unless they have a valid basis for refuting the random walk hypothesis as it applies to movements in the market average.</p>
          </abstract>
